revision.text:
The [[Affix|suffix]] '''–ol''' is used in [[organic chemistry]] principally to form names of [[organic compound]]s containing the [[hydroxyl]] (–OH) group, mainly [[alcohol]]s (also [[phenol]]). The suffix was extracted from the word ''[[alcohol]]''.

The suffix also appears in some [[trivial name]]s with reference to [[oil]]s (from Latin ''oleum'', oil). Examples of this [[word sense|sense]] of the suffix include [[Phenol|benzol]], [[eugenol]], [[urushiol]], [[xylol]], and [[menthol]].

