'''Vuppuluri Ganapathi Sastry''' (1898–1989) was an Indian [[sanskrit]] scholar, writer and spiritual teacher, known for his scholarship in [[Vedas]]. He was the author of ''Veda Sara Ratnavali'', a text on [[Vedas]]. 

Ganapathi Sastry was born on December 16, 1898 at [[Kakinada]] in the south Indian state of [[Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name="Welcome to SRIVGVP">{{Cite web |url=http://www.srivgvp.org/sriganapathi.asp |title=Welcome to SRIVGVP |website=www.srivgvp.org |access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> ''Veda Sara Ratnavali'', a two-part text on Vedas,<ref name="Vedasaara RatnavaliPart II">{{Cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/VedasaaraRatnavaliPartII |title=Vedasaara RatnavaliPart II |last=Uppuluri Ganapathi Sastri |date=2018-06-02 |language=Sanskrit |access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> was written for the Endowments Department of the [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]].<ref name="Publications">{{Cite web |url=http://www.srivgvp.org/publications.asp |title=Publications |date=2018-06-02 |website=www.srivgvp.org |access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref> The [[Government of India]] awarded him the [[Padma Bhushan]], the third highest civilian award, in 1985.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dashboard-padmaawards.gov.in/ |title=Padma Awards |date=2018-05-17 |website=Padma Awards |publisher=Government of India |access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref> Sastry died on July 17, 1989.<ref name="Welcome to SRIVGVP" /> Sri Vuppluri Ganapathi Sastry Veda Sastra Parishat (VGVP), a non-government organization for the propagation of vedas, is named after him.<ref name="Overview">{{Cite web |url=http://www.srivgvp.org/overview.asp |title=Overview |date=2018-06-02 |website=www.srivgvp.org |access-date=2018-06-02}}</ref>

